<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF6F6AD0F82D919D172FB242" pageId="148" pageNumber="909" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF6F6AD0F82D919D172FB242" blockId="148.[2000,2594,1909,2336]" lastBlockId="148.[1390,2598,2343,3481]" pageId="148" pageNumber="909">
Relationships uncertain but limited genetic data place this species as sister to the M. 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF6F6AD0F7C59E4F16C1B301" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1872" box="[2105,2241,2070,2099]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="909" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucogaster">leucogaster</taxonomicName>
clade (see above). Often considered a race of M. 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF6F6AD0F6D09E6317B4B369" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1872" box="[2348,2484,2106,2139]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="909" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucogaster">leucogaster</taxonomicName>
but numerous genetic and morphological studies support their treatment at separate species. Race sibirica has occasionally been treated as a distinct species, but morphological data do not support this. The name 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF6F6AD0FA8C9F7E1BF5B27A" authorityName="Hill &amp; Francis" authorityYear="1984" box="[1392,1525,2343,2376]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Kerivoula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="909" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="intermedia">intermedia</taxonomicName>
is here considered to be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF6F6AD0F7E79F7E166CB27A" authorityName="Kishida" authorityYear="1927" box="[2075,2156,2343,2376]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Plecotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="909" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ognevi">ognevi</taxonomicName>
, although further morphological and genetic comparison is needed. Three subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
